<td data-valign="top"><p>MOCH La Luan Casg,<br />
Chunna mi air sal<br />
Lach is eala bhan<br />
     A snamh le cheile.</p>
<p>Chuala mi Di-mart<br />
Eunarag nan trath,<br />
Meannanaich ’s an ard<br />
     ’S ag eigheach.</p>
<p>Di-ciadain bha mi<br />
Buain na feamain-chir,<br />
Is chunna mi na tri<br />
     Ri eirigh.</p>
<p>Dh’ aithnich mi air ball<br />
Gun robh an imirig ann,<br />
Beannachd nach biodh ann<br />
     An deigh sin.</p>
<p>Comraig Bhride bhith,<br />
Comraig Mhoire mhin,<br />
Comraig Mhicheil mhil,<br />
Dhomh fhi’ ’s dha m’ eudail,<br />
     Dhomh fhi’ ’s dha m’ eudail.</p></td>
<td data-valign="top"><p> </p></td>
<td data-valign="top"><p>EARLY on the day of Easter Monday,<br />
I saw on the brine<br />
A duck and a white swan<br />
     Swim together.</p>
<p>I heard on Tuesday<br />
The snipe of the seasons,<br />
Bleating on high<br />
     And calling.</p>
<p>On Wednesday I had been<br />
Cutting the channelled fucus,<br />
And then saw I the three<br />
     Arising.</p>
<p>I knew immediately<br />
That a flitting there was,<br />
Blessing there would not be<br />
     After that.</p>
<p>The girth of Bride calm,<br />
The girth of Mary mild,<br />
The girth of Michael strong,<br />
Upon me and mine,<br />
     Upon me and mine.</p></td>
